h4. Steps to Reproduce:
# Create two projects, project A and project B;
# Create a [permission scheme|https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/JIRA051/Managing+Project+Permissions] restricting _Browse Projects_ on project B to a specific group;
# [Link|https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/JIRA/Linking+Issues] an issue of project A to another issue on project B.
# Access the issue of project A with an user that is not member of the group with _Browse Projects_ permission.

h4. Actual Results:
JIRA does not displays the Issue Links section (as expected), but the issue key of project B is still displayed at the History/Activity/All tabs, it only removes the hyper-link. See this screenshot:
!Issue.png!

h4. Expected Results:
The issue key of project B should not be displayed at the History/Activity/All, It may be considered as a security leak for some companies.

